<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,856,2024]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,356,927,952]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">DIAGNOSIS</emphasis>
: The only extant species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Edwards" authorityYear="1925" box="[713,875,928,952]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[713,875,928,952]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Leptomorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the following combination of characters: Laterotergite and anepisternum brown; wing without apical spot (
<figureCitation box="[882,965,963,987]" captionStart="FIGURES 42–55" captionStartId="92.[151,263,1812,1835]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,177,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-169@92.[151,1436,177,1803]" captionTargetPageId="92" captionText="FIGURES 42–55. Leptomorphus wings. 42. L. aliciae, dorsal. 43. L. amorimi paratype female, dorsal. 44. L. babai holotype male, ventral. 45. L. bifasciatus lectotype, ventral. 46. L. brandiae paratype female, dorsal. 47. L. carnevalei allotype, dorsal. 48. L. chaseni holotype female, dorsal. 49. L. couturieri, ventral. 50 L. crassipilus holotype male, ventral. 51. L. crosskeyi, ventral. 52. L. eberhardi paratype female, ventral. 53. L. fasciculatus paratype male, dorsal. 54. L. femoratus holotype male, ventral. 55. L. forcipatus dorsal. Abbreviations: A1, A2 = Anal veins; C = costa; CuA = anterior branch of cubitus; CuP = posterior branch of cubitus; h = humeral crossvein; M1, M2, M4, = branches of the media; r-m = radial-medial crossvein; Rs = radial sector vein; R1, R4, R5 = branches of the radius; Sc = subcosta; sc-r = subcostal-radial crossvein." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
); vein sc-r joining R within its own length of origin of Rs; segments 3–5 of abdomen noticeably swollen relative to other segments. Male unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,856,2024]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
This species can be distinguished from the other 
<collectingRegion box="[729,819,1035,1059]" country="Republic of the Congo" name="Orientale" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Oriental</collectingRegion>
and eastern Palaearctic species in this manuscript, based on the dark brown colour of the katepisternum and metepisternum (
<figureCitation box="[884,950,1071,1095]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9" captionStartId="84.[151,264,1764,1787]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,183,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-49@84.[151,1436,181,1746]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. Leptomorphus habitus. 5. L. bifasciatus, neotype male. 6. L. brandiae, paratype male (in ethanol). 7. L. chaseni, holotype female. 8. L. carnevalei, male. 9. L. couturieri, male." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
, both completely yellow in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Matile" authorityYear="1977" box="[1251,1342,1071,1095]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="babai">
<emphasis box="[1251,1342,1071,1095]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. babai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1356,1420,1071,1095]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="83.[151,263,1566,1589]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,289,1543]" captionTargetId="figure-45@83.[151,1436,287,1544]" captionTargetPageId="83" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Leptomorphus habitus. 1. L. aliciae, male. 2. L. babai, paratype male. 3. L. amorimi, paratype female. 4. L. bifasciatus, female." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[151,263,1107,1130]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatus">
<emphasis box="[151,263,1107,1130]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. ornatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[277,356,1106,1130]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–33" captionStartId="89.[151,263,1758,1781]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,223,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-41@89.[151,1436,217,1737]" captionTargetPageId="89" captionText="FIGURES 30–33. Leptomorphus habitus. 30. L. ornatus, female. 31. L. panorpiformis, male. 32. L. perplexus, paratype female. 33. L. quadrimaculatus, male." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Borkent" authorityYear="2012" box="[415,598,1107,1130]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="titiwangsensis">
<emphasis box="[415,598,1107,1130]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. titiwangsensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[612,693,1106,1130]" captionStart="FIGURES 38–41" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1941,1964]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,258,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-40@91.[151,1436,255,1920]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 38–41. Leptomorphus habitus. 38. L. titiwangsensis, paratype female. 39. L. waodani, holotype male. 40. L. tagbanua, holotype male. 41. L. walkeri, male." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
); metepisternum light brown in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Borkent" authorityYear="2012" box="[1041,1157,1107,1131]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tabatius">
<emphasis box="[1041,1157,1107,1131]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. tabatius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1171,1250,1106,1130]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–37" captionStartId="90.[151,263,1623,1646]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,181,1602]" captionTargetId="figure-41@90.[151,1436,179,1602]" captionTargetPageId="90" captionText="FIGURES 34–37. Leptomorphus habitus. 34. L. stigmatus, holotype male. 35. L. tabatius, holotype male. 36. L. subcaeruleus, male. 37. L. subcaeruleus, female." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
) and half brown/ half yellow in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Borkent" authorityYear="2012" box="[310,444,1142,1166]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tagbanua">
<emphasis box="[310,444,1142,1166]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. tagbanua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[458,540,1142,1166]" captionStart="FIGURES 38–41" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1941,1964]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,258,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-40@91.[151,1436,255,1920]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 38–41. Leptomorphus habitus. 38. L. titiwangsensis, paratype female. 39. L. waodani, holotype male. 40. L. tagbanua, holotype male. 41. L. walkeri, male." pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
)). The lack of adequate description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Papp, L. &amp; Sevcik, J." box="[969,1214,1142,1166]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="139 - 159" refId="ref95170" refString="Papp, L. &amp; Sevcik, J. (2011) Eight new oriental and Australasian species of Leptomorphus (Diptera: Mycetophilidae). Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientarum Hungaricae, 57, 139 - 159." type="journal article" year="2011">Papp &amp; Ševčík (2011)</bibRefCitation>
makes it difficult to distinguish this species from theirs, especially as 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Matile" authorityYear="1977" box="[688,801,1178,1202]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chaseni">
<emphasis box="[688,801,1178,1202]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. chaseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the female.
</paragraph>
